# gen32: the text -> facts bridge. "read: <passage>" splits a passage into
# clauses and feeds each to the existing assertion parsers (quantity, cause,
# knowledge), asserting what parses into the session KB and *counting* what
# does not. This is the wall the gen28-gen31 run kept naming: the reasoning
# primitives existed, but nothing turned prose into facts. The extractor lifts
# only sentence shapes parrot0 already knows -- it does not understand open
# prose, and the skipped count is the honest measure of that (Decision
# D-2026-06-15e). Held-out content.
#
# One passage populates the KB; the unparseable sentence is skipped, not faked.
# (The decimal-safe splitter keeps "1.3"-style numbers intact.)
> read: zibo has 2 gold. nibo has 5 gold. fire causes smoke. tariq is a knight. every knight is a noble. the market square was unusually crowded that morning.
< Learned 5 fact(s), skipped 1.
# Now every gen28-gen31 primitive answers from the *extracted* facts.
> does nibo have more gold than zibo?
< Yes.
> what is the effect of fire?
< smoke.
> is tariq a noble?
< Yes.
> how many gold does zibo have?
< zibo has 2 gold.
# A passage of only unparseable prose learns nothing -- and admits it.
> read: the weather was lovely. nobody knew what would happen next.
< Learned 0 fact(s), skipped 2.